## Risks

1. **Pre-existing build break in `cognicode-mcp-server` bin
   (NOT introduced by this PR)** — `server.rs` imports
   `opentelemetry_prometheus::Prometheus` and uses
   `Prometheus::default()` and `exporter.export()`. None of these
   exist in opentelemetry-prometheus 0.27; the new API requires a
   global `Registry` + `SdkMeterProvider` + `Meter` setup at
   startup. PR-1 likely introduced this during the
   opentelemetry-prometheus 0.16 → 0.27 upgrade, and PR-2's
   verify (`cargo build -p cognicode-mcp --release` — which only
   builds the `cognicode-mcp` stdio bin, NOT the
   `cognicode-mcp-server` HTTP/SSE bin) did not catch it. To
   unblock the M3.5 test build, this PR:
   - extracts the auth logic to a new `[lib]` target so it can
     be unit-tested without compiling the broken bin;
   - leaves the broken `metrics_handler` in `server.rs` as-is
     (out of M3.5 scope; the previous maintainers should fix
     it as a follow-up);
   - documents the issue in the runbook §9.5 and the SLO doc
     §1.
   **Mitigation**: production deploys use the containerised
   `cognicode-mcp` image, which uses the stdio bin (not
   affected). The HTTP/SSE mode in the repo is in the same
   broken state in `main` as it was before this PR.

2. **Token comparison reads env var on every request** — the
   middleware reads `COGNICODE_MCP_AUTH_TOKEN` per request
   rather than caching at startup. This is intentional: it
   lets an operator rotate the token by simply restarting
   the container. Cost is one `std::env::var` syscall per
   request, which is negligible compared to the cost of an
   MCP tool dispatch. If this becomes a hotspot, swap to
   `OnceLock<String>` and document the rotation procedure
   (which then becomes "set the env var AND send SIGHUP").

3. **Auth layer exempts `/health`, `/ready`, `/metrics`** — a
   misconfigured operator could expose these to the public
   internet and accidentally leak health/metrics state. The
   runbook §7.4 explicitly says "bind to a private interface"
   and the SLO doc §5 is a "do not page" reminder, but the
   enforcement is on the operator, not the binary. If we want
   a tighter posture, add a `COGNICODE_MCP_AUTH_REQUIRED_ON_PROBES`
   env var in a follow-up that, when set, applies the auth
   layer to the public_routes router too.

4. **No integration test for the full middleware pipeline**
   — the unit tests cover `check_bearer_token` (the security-
   critical branch logic) but not the `auth_middleware`
   closure (the env-var read + state extraction glue). A
   full integration test would need a `Router::oneshot`
   harness with a `tower::ServiceExt::oneshot` and an env
   var manipulation. `std::env::set_var` in parallel tests
   is racy, so the source-level invariant (the first match
   arm returns `Ok(next.run(request).await)` on
   `Err(_)`/`Ok("")`) is documented in code comments
   instead. Recommend adding a serial test (via `serial_test`
   crate) in a follow-up if this becomes a regression source.

5. **`.gitignore` blanket `.github` removal is a one-way
   door** — once committed, future workflow files
   (dependabot, codeowners, ISSUE_TEMPLATE, etc.) will be
   committed by default. The previous rule was an
   over-broad cleanup-era line, so this is the right call,
   but it's a small policy change worth flagging in the PR
   description.

